{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"caaa9000-494e-41a7-9478-82f36a4e32e1","content":"Here's what I found in `my_app/views.py`:\n\n**Line 3 — `datetime.now()`** — This is a hard-coded static call that makes the function difficult to test because you can't control or predict the returned time.\n\n### Recommended fix\n\nUse Django's `timezone.now()` via dependency injection or `freezegun`/`time_machine` for tests. The simplest production-friendly approach is to use Django's `timezone.now()` (timezone-aware) and then freeze time in tests:\n\n```python\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\ndef index(request):\n    now = timezone.now()\n    return render(request, 'index.html', {'time': now})\n```\n\nThen in tests, use [`freezegun`](https://pypi.org/project/freezegun/) or [`time-machine`](https://pypi.org/project/time-machine/):\n\n```python\nfrom freezegun import freeze_time\n\n@freeze_time(\"2026-04-25 12:00:00\")\ndef test_index(self):\n    response = self.client.get(\"/\")\n    # now you can assert against a known time\n```\n\nThis was the only file in `my_app/` — just the one `datetime.now()` call to address.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4350e905-bec1-4921-b109-44f6020192c6","outputTokens":302,"requestId":"CFC2:1C9612:17428AE:1B4010B:69EC2846"},"id":"d26edd7b-c236-4ad7-9fd0-f806ff26c6bd","timestamp":"2026-04-25T02:34:54.424Z","parentId":"5ad3734f-19e0-4776-9920-b978839dd411"}
